The results show that Logistic Regression and Naive Bayes are the strongest models for predicting heart disease in this dataset,
both achieving an accuracy of approximately 88% on the test set. Logistic Regression has the highest precision (0.92), 
meaning it produces fewer false positives, while Naive Bayes has slightly higher recall (0.87), making it better at identifying actual
cases of heart disease. The Decision Tree, with a shallow depth of 2, is less accurate at around 81% but remains highly interpretable,
allowing one to easily understand the decision rules. Cross-validation confirms these findings, showing stable performance for all models, 
with Decision Tree being slightly less consistent across folds. Overall, Logistic Regression is best for minimizing false alarms,
Naive Bayes is slightly better at catching positive cases, and the Decision Tree provides a simple, interpretable model.
